		<command:details>
			<command:name>Start-PWebServer</command:name>
			<maml:description>
				<maml:para>Starts a new web server instance</maml:para>
			</maml:description>
			<maml:copyright>
				<maml:para />
			</maml:copyright>
			<command:verb>Start</command:verb>
			<command:noun>PWebServer</command:noun>
			<dev:version />
		</command:details>
		<maml:description>
			<maml:para>The Start-PWebServer cmdlet starts a new web server instance. The server will serve static content from a folder of your choice, and optionally relay some requests to another server, acting as a proxy.</maml:para>
			<maml:para>In its most simplistic use, you can simply call Start-PWebServer from a given folder, and a web server will start at http://localhost:8080 serving the contents of the current powershell directory. You can use cmdlet parameters to change the served folder, port, protocol and/or listening prefix. See the syntax section for help with this and other parameters.</maml:para>
			<maml:para>To serve https, you will need to create an https certificate and bind it to the desired interface/port. See about_PWeb_Certificates for help.</maml:para>
			<maml:para>To configure advanced options, you can create a server.json file in the directory being served. See about_PWeb_Config for details on the syntax of this file. A template of server.json can be created using the cmdlet New-PWebConfig.</maml:para>
			<maml:para>If you configure your server to relay requests to another server (using server.json), it should be able to handshake and maintain websockets upgraded from http requests. The PWebServer will try to stablish a websocket connection with your backed using the same level of security you stablished in the server.json file, meaning that if you configured your backed server to be reached through &#39;http&#39;, the websocket will be stablished using &#39;ws&#39;, and if you configured your backed server to be reached through &#39;https&#39;, the websocket will be stablished using &#39;wss&#39;.</maml:para>
		</maml:description>
		<command:syntax>
			<command:syntaxItem>
				<maml:name>Start-PWebServer</maml:name>
				<command:parameter required="false" variableLength="false" globbing="false" pipelineInput="false" position="0">
					<maml:name>Folder</maml:name>
					<maml:description>
						<maml:para>String representing the directory to be served. If not specified, the current directory is used.</maml:para>
					</maml:description>
					<command:parameterValue required="true" variableLength="false">String</command:parameterValue>
				</command:parameter>
				<command:parameter required="false" variableLength="false" globbing="false" pipelineInput="false" position="named">
					<maml:name>Secure</maml:name>
					<maml:description>
						<maml:para>Use secure protocol (https).</maml:para>
					</maml:description>
					<command:parameterValue required="true" variableLength="false">SwitchParameter</command:parameterValue>
				</command:parameter>
				<command:parameter required="false" variableLength="false" globbing="false" pipelineInput="false" position="named">
					<maml:name>ListenAt</maml:name>
					<maml:description>
						<maml:para>Prefix used by the http listener. Usually an ip or dns name.
The default is &#39;localhost&#39; if you are not running elevated, and &#39;+&#39; if you are running elevated.
The prefix &#39;+&#39; tells the server to listen on all interfaces. Similarly, with &#39;*&#39; the server will also handle requests from all interfaces, but only if the request has not been handled yet.</maml:para>
					</maml:description>
					<command:parameterValue required="true" variableLength="false">String</command:parameterValue>
				</command:parameter>
				<command:parameter required="false" variableLength="false" globbing="false" pipelineInput="false" position="named">
					<maml:name>Port</maml:name>
					<maml:description>
						<maml:para>Specifies the TCP port used by your server. Defaults to 8080 if you are not running elevated, otherwise the defaults are 80 for http and 443 for https</maml:para>
					</maml:description>
					<command:parameterValue required="true" variableLength="false">Int32</command:parameterValue>
				</command:parameter>
				<command:parameter required="false" variableLength="false" globbing="false" pipelineInput="false" position="named">
					<maml:name>ShowIps</maml:name>
					<maml:description>
						<maml:para>Use to print all your ips in the console before starting the server.</maml:para>
					</maml:description>
					<command:parameterValue required="false" variableLength="false">SwitchParameter</command:parameterValue>
				</command:parameter>
			</command:syntaxItem>
		</command:syntax>
		<command:parameters>
			<command:parameter required="false" variableLength="false" globbing="false" pipelineInput="false" position="0">
				<maml:name>Folder</maml:name>
				<maml:description>
					<maml:para>String representing the directory to be served. If not specified, the current directory is used.</maml:para>
				</maml:description>
				<command:parameterValue required="true" variableLength="false">String</command:parameterValue>
				<dev:type>
					<maml:name>String</maml:name>
					<maml:uri/>
				</dev:type>
				<dev:defaultValue>.</dev:defaultValue>
			</command:parameter>
			<command:parameter required="false" variableLength="false" globbing="false" pipelineInput="false" position="named">
				<maml:name>Secure</maml:name>
				<maml:description>
					<maml:para>Use secure protocol (https).</maml:para>
				</maml:description>
				<command:parameterValue required="false" variableLength="false">SwitchParameter</command:parameterValue>
				<dev:type>
					<maml:name>SwitchParameter</maml:name>
					<maml:uri/>
				</dev:type>
				<dev:defaultValue>False</dev:defaultValue>
			</command:parameter>
			<command:parameter required="false" variableLength="false" globbing="false" pipelineInput="false" position="named">
				<maml:name>ListenAt</maml:name>
				<maml:description>
					<maml:para>Prefix used by the http listener. Usually an ip or dns name.
The default is &#39;localhost&#39; if you are not running elevated, and &#39;+&#39; if you are running elevated.
The prefix &#39;+&#39; tells the server to listen on all interfaces. Similarly, with &#39;*&#39; the server will also handle requests from all interfaces, but only if the request has not been handled yet.</maml:para>
				</maml:description>
				<command:parameterValue required="false" variableLength="false">String</command:parameterValue>
				<dev:type>
					<maml:name>String</maml:name>
					<maml:uri/>
				</dev:type>
				<dev:defaultValue>&apos;localhost&apos; or &apos;+&apos;</dev:defaultValue>
			</command:parameter>
			<command:parameter required="false" variableLength="false" globbing="false" pipelineInput="false" position="named">
				<maml:name>Port</maml:name>
				<maml:description>
					<maml:para>Specifies the TCP port used by your server. Defaults to 8080 if you are not running elevated, otherwise the defaults are 80 for http and 443 for https</maml:para>
				</maml:description>
				<command:parameterValue required="false" variableLength="false">Int32</command:parameterValue>
				<dev:type>
					<maml:name>Int32</maml:name>
					<maml:uri/>
				</dev:type>
				<dev:defaultValue>8080, 80 or 443</dev:defaultValue>
			</command:parameter>
			<command:parameter required="false" variableLength="false" globbing="false" pipelineInput="false" position="named">
				<maml:name>ShowIps</maml:name>
				<maml:description>
					<maml:para>Use to print all your ips in the console before starting the server.</maml:para>
